2
00:01:48,399 --> 00:01:49,399
[Rumbling]

3
00:01:56,032 --> 00:01:57,032
[Electronic beeping]

4
00:02:53,590 --> 00:02:54,590
[Guns clicking]

5
00:03:54,651 --> 00:03:55,817
[Groaning]

6
00:04:31,813 --> 00:04:32,813
[Sighing]

7
00:04:37,694 --> 00:04:38,694
[Laughing]

8
00:04:51,624 --> 00:04:52,708
Stop!

9
00:05:11,394 --> 00:05:12,769
Hey, y'all

10
00:05:14,397 --> 00:05:15,731
[Upbeat techno music playing]

11
00:05:32,248 --> 00:05:34,082
Little bugger!

12
00:05:36,127 --> 00:05:38,295
Not live rounds, Lara.

13
00:05:38,755 --> 00:05:41,590
He's in real pain right now.

14
00:05:41,924 --> 00:05:46,178
This is a major remodel.
This is a disaster.

15
00:05:46,262 --> 00:05:50,015
Was it programmed to stop before it
took my head off?

16
00:05:50,099 --> 00:05:53,769
Ah, well, that would be a no.

17
00:05:55,271 --> 00:05:57,689
But you said make it more challenging,
so....

18
00:05:57,774 --> 00:05:59,608
Hence, the live fire.

19
00:06:04,864 --> 00:06:07,115
Live rounds again.

20
00:06:07,617 --> 00:06:09,201
Poor Simon.

21
00:06:09,452 --> 00:06:11,495
What has she done to you?

22
00:06:26,302 --> 00:06:27,386
[Music stops]

23
00:07:08,386 --> 00:07:10,345
Oh. Very funny.

24
00:07:10,430 --> 00:07:12,848
I'm only trying to turn you into a lady.

25
00:07:15,560 --> 00:07:17,436
And a lady should be modest.

26
00:07:17,520 --> 00:07:20,313
Yes, a lady should be modest.

27
00:07:26,612 --> 00:07:28,196
[Bells tolling]

28
00:07:35,913 --> 00:07:38,373
MAN: Brothers and sisters...

29
00:07:38,458 --> 00:07:41,918
today is the 1 5th of May...

30
00:07:42,003 --> 00:07:46,256
the first day of the planetary alignment...

31
00:07:46,340 --> 00:07:50,719
and we are still no nearer to discovering
the location of the key.

32
00:07:50,803 --> 00:07:52,429
It seems...

33
00:07:52,513 --> 00:07:55,390
we are running out of time.

34
00:07:55,433 --> 00:07:57,851
This is not acceptable.

35
00:07:59,479 --> 00:08:03,690
Mr. Powell,
your explanation for this, please?

36
00:08:04,817 --> 00:08:08,737
I have no explanation.
Certainly no excuses.

37
00:08:08,821 --> 00:08:12,491
Except to once again
respectfully remind the council...

38
00:08:12,575 --> 00:08:14,242
that we are working from clues...

39
00:08:14,327 --> 00:08:17,162
based on
ancient cosmological models...

40
00:08:18,331 --> 00:08:21,082
predating Aristotle.

41
00:08:21,167 --> 00:08:24,794
But I'm happy to announce
that we're almost ready.

42
00:08:24,879 --> 00:08:28,089
And I am supremely confident...

43
00:08:28,174 --> 00:08:32,594
that we will have our answer in time
for the relevant planetary alignment.

44
00:08:32,678 --> 00:08:36,515
So, we will have possession
of the key in...

45
00:08:37,517 --> 00:08:39,226
one week.

46
00:08:39,936 --> 00:08:43,355
Yes, indeed. One week.

47
00:08:43,439 --> 00:08:47,776
This is good news, Mr. Powell,
but remember...

48
00:08:47,860 --> 00:08:50,612
we have only a single opportunity...

49
00:08:50,696 --> 00:08:54,074
to retrieve the two halves of the triangle.

50
00:08:54,116 --> 00:08:56,785
And if we fail...

51
00:08:56,869 --> 00:09:00,789
we must wait another 5,000 years.

52
00:09:03,042 --> 00:09:04,834
I don't know about you,
but that's more time...

53
00:09:04,919 --> 00:09:08,046
than I am prepared to commit
to this enterprise.

54
00:09:09,465 --> 00:09:11,132
We shall be ready.

55
00:09:13,344 --> 00:09:14,636
Trust me.

56
00:09:26,482 --> 00:09:29,401
-We're not.... We're not ready, are we?
-No.

57
00:09:35,533 --> 00:09:39,035
Good morning, Lara.
And what a beautiful morning it is.

58
00:09:40,621 --> 00:09:42,664
Back to work, I'm afraid.

59
00:09:44,166 --> 00:09:45,959
It's adventure time.

60
00:09:48,754 --> 00:09:50,171
Egypt again.

61
00:09:51,674 --> 00:09:53,925
It's nothing but pyramids and sand.

62
00:09:54,010 --> 00:09:56,970
I know. Gets everywhere. In the cracks.

63
00:10:00,766 --> 00:10:02,392
Spanish galleon?

64
00:10:04,979 --> 00:10:07,522
Do you know what day it is, Hillary?

65
00:10:08,941 --> 00:10:11,526
Yes, of course.

66
00:10:13,404 --> 00:10:14,696
The 15th.

67
00:10:16,282 --> 00:10:18,533
And that is never a good day.

68
00:10:42,558 --> 00:10:44,225
I miss you, Daddy.

69
00:10:46,479 --> 00:10:50,148
I wish we could get back the time
that was stolen from us.

70
00:11:13,923 --> 00:11:16,591
LARA: My father
would loved to have seen this.

71
00:11:18,302 --> 00:11:22,097
Tonight Pluto and Neptune
align with Uranus.

72
00:11:22,139 --> 00:11:24,599
It's the first stage of the alignment
of all nine planets...

73
00:11:24,684 --> 00:11:27,894
culminating in a full solar eclipse.

74
00:11:27,937 --> 00:11:31,064
It only happens once every 5,000 years.

75
00:11:31,107 --> 00:11:32,941
When is the eclipse?

76
00:11:33,192 --> 00:11:34,984
One week from today.

77
00:11:36,112 --> 00:11:39,989
But there is plenty to look out for
until then.

78
00:11:41,701 --> 00:11:43,118
Incredible.

79
00:12:00,594 --> 00:12:01,594
[Groaning]

80
00:12:15,609 --> 00:12:19,279
I wish you could remember her.
She loved you so much.

81
00:12:19,321 --> 00:12:21,030
Mummy!

82
00:12:22,658 --> 00:12:25,785
I wish I could remember her, too.

83
00:12:25,828 --> 00:12:28,955
-I still have you, Daddy.
-Yes, you do.

84
00:12:34,170 --> 00:12:38,798
The exact alignment of the planets
necessary to activate the triangle...

85
00:12:38,841 --> 00:12:43,303
only occurs once every 5,000 years.

86
00:12:44,096 --> 00:12:47,682
But that will prove to be
just long enough...

87
00:12:47,767 --> 00:12:51,102
for little Lara Croft to grow up...

88
00:12:51,187 --> 00:12:53,813
and to find it.

89
00:12:55,191 --> 00:12:57,025
[Clock ticking]

90
00:13:26,555 --> 00:13:28,932
[Ticking]

91
00:14:03,092 --> 00:14:04,092
[Ticking echoing]

92
00:14:55,477 --> 00:14:56,853
Bryce!

93
00:14:58,898 --> 00:15:00,565
Hello, fellas.

94
00:15:01,317 --> 00:15:03,276
-How's business?
-Bryce!

95
00:15:04,653 --> 00:15:07,572
Okay, okay. I'm coming. I'm coming.

96
00:15:11,327 --> 00:15:14,329
We have 83 rooms.
Why can't you live in the house?

97
00:15:14,371 --> 00:15:16,956
Well, I'm a free spirit, me.

98
00:15:16,999 --> 00:15:18,166
Right.

99
00:15:20,419 --> 00:15:21,711
What's that smell?

100
00:15:21,795 --> 00:15:24,464
5:00 a.m. Let's go.

101
00:15:27,843 --> 00:15:29,844
This had better be good.

102
00:15:34,183 --> 00:15:35,683
It's a clock.

103
00:15:36,185 --> 00:15:39,687
I found it last night. It was ticking.

104
00:15:43,150 --> 00:15:45,860
Must be one of them ticking clocks, eh?

105
00:15:46,820 --> 00:15:49,155
It was hidden in a secret room.

106
00:15:50,366 --> 00:15:51,366
Bryce.

107
00:15:52,868 --> 00:15:54,619
Don't start.

108
00:15:54,703 --> 00:15:59,666
Well, Lara, it's a clock. It ticks.
It tells the time. It's wrong.

109
00:16:00,042 --> 00:16:01,751
It started ticking...

110
00:16:01,835 --> 00:16:05,129
last night during the first stage
of the alignment.

111
00:16:06,090 --> 00:16:07,090
Oh.

112
00:16:10,094 --> 00:16:12,345
Well, gonna need some coffee.

113
00:16:17,226 --> 00:16:19,519
Okay, in we go.

114
00:16:22,481 --> 00:16:24,399
Looks pretty ordinary to me.

115
00:16:24,483 --> 00:16:26,234
Well, keep looking.

116
00:16:30,364 --> 00:16:34,242
Your coffee, sir.
Decaf latte with non-fat milk.

117
00:16:35,619 --> 00:16:39,414
Oh, champion. Steaming sump oil.

118
00:16:44,253 --> 00:16:47,171
Wait. What did you do?

119
00:16:47,256 --> 00:16:50,633
-I don't know. What did I do?
-Where is that?

120
00:16:50,718 --> 00:16:53,678
I don't know.
I just took my hand off the fiber optics.

121
00:16:53,762 --> 00:16:55,430
What is that?

122
00:16:55,514 --> 00:16:58,766
-Oh, bugger!
-Bugger.

123
00:17:03,439 --> 00:17:06,107
Screw 1 3 to quadrant four.

124
00:17:07,067 --> 00:17:11,446
-Screw 14 to quadrant three.
-Oh, please.

125
00:17:12,656 --> 00:17:15,783
It's my map,
so I know where they all came from.

126
00:17:17,119 --> 00:17:18,745
It's camouflage.

127
00:17:30,132 --> 00:17:32,133
Okay.

128
00:17:42,436 --> 00:17:43,978
Hidden within.

129
00:17:47,191 --> 00:17:48,691
What is that?

130
00:17:53,697 --> 00:17:55,490
The All Seeing Eye.

131
00:18:08,128 --> 00:18:12,799
Lot 1 21 , a Louis XV Ormolu
mounted bracket clock.

132
00:18:13,008 --> 00:18:17,053
Showing on my left, £1 ,800,000.

133
00:18:17,137 --> 00:18:20,973
£1 ,800,000. Thank you.
£1 ,800,000. £1 ,900,000.

134
00:18:21,016 --> 00:18:22,934
£2,000,000. £2,000,000, now.

135
00:18:23,018 --> 00:18:26,020
£2,1 00,000. £2,1 00,000, now.

136
00:18:26,105 --> 00:18:30,525
£2,1 00,000.
Any advance on £2,1 00,000?

137
00:18:30,609 --> 00:18:33,986
Any more?
£2,1 00,000. £2,200,000. Thank you, sir.

138
00:18:34,029 --> 00:18:36,781
£2,200,000 now.

139
00:18:36,865 --> 00:18:39,951
At £2,200,000. £2,300,000.

140
00:18:40,035 --> 00:18:42,120
£2,300,000. £2,400,000.

141
00:18:42,204 --> 00:18:46,707
Lady's bid, £2,400,000 now. £2,400,000.

142
00:18:46,792 --> 00:18:48,835
Against you, sir. Two million five? No.

143
00:18:48,877 --> 00:18:52,338
£2,400,000, then.
Lady's bid at £2,400,000.

144
00:18:52,381 --> 00:18:54,090
£2,500,000.

145
00:18:54,174 --> 00:18:57,718
In a new place at £2,500,000.

146
00:18:57,761 --> 00:19:01,472
Any more at £2,500,000?

147
00:19:02,391 --> 00:19:03,724
Sold.

148
00:19:05,310 --> 00:19:07,395
Lara, my dear.

149
00:19:08,021 --> 00:19:09,647
-Mr. Wilson.
-Let's go into my study.

150
00:19:09,731 --> 00:19:11,899
Let me take that for you.

151
00:19:11,942 --> 00:19:14,652
Lara Croft. I don't believe it.

152
00:19:16,697 --> 00:19:19,490
-I'll just be a minute.
-Hi.

153
00:19:23,954 --> 00:19:26,914
You still pretending to be
a photojournalist?

154
00:19:27,416 --> 00:19:31,127
You know, I think it's really cool
that you still have a day job...

155
00:19:32,254 --> 00:19:35,089
even though it's obviously just for show.

156
00:19:35,382 --> 00:19:39,302
So, Alex, are you still pretending
to be an archaeologist?

157
00:19:44,641 --> 00:19:46,058
Do we always have to fight like this?

158
00:19:46,101 --> 00:19:48,436
I mean, maybe we don't.

159
00:19:49,438 --> 00:19:51,439
-Maybe we do.
-Why?

160
00:19:51,481 --> 00:19:54,317
-You stole my prayer wheels.
-Stole? Stole?

161
00:19:54,401 --> 00:19:56,360
From you? You know, that's funny.
You know, it's....

162
00:19:56,445 --> 00:19:59,822
It's not like you ever really owned them
or anything.

163
00:20:01,450 --> 00:20:03,492
Hey, you're the tomb raider.

164
00:20:03,577 --> 00:20:05,369
MAN: Mr. West, we are ready for you.

165
00:20:05,454 --> 00:20:08,456
Oh, I think your clients need you.

166
00:20:09,791 --> 00:20:12,793
Go ahead. You're wanted on the floor.

167
00:20:12,836 --> 00:20:17,006
After all, as you once said
so memorably, "It's all just a business."

168
00:20:17,090 --> 00:20:19,550
Right? So go do business.

169
00:20:19,635 --> 00:20:20,676
Go.

170
00:20:21,803 --> 00:20:22,803
Lara?

171
00:20:44,660 --> 00:20:49,497
Lara, this is a unique object.

172
00:20:50,332 --> 00:20:52,833
Only one of the dials is working.

173
00:20:52,876 --> 00:20:55,211
It glows, like the eye, lesser.

174
00:20:56,380 --> 00:20:58,798
But it seems to be getting brighter.

175
00:20:58,840 --> 00:21:01,300
And it's also running backwards...

176
00:21:01,343 --> 00:21:04,679
like it's not so much keeping time,
but counting down to something.

177
00:21:04,763 --> 00:21:06,013
-Yes.
-And look at the back.

178
00:21:06,098 --> 00:21:10,601
It's as though it fits into something,
almost like a key.

179
00:21:13,438 --> 00:21:17,900
Yes. Yes, fascinating.
Incredibly beautiful.

180
00:21:19,611 --> 00:21:20,861
My father once told me...

181
00:21:20,904 --> 00:21:23,572
of a magical triangle
stamped with the All Seeing Eye.

182
00:21:23,657 --> 00:21:26,742
He said it gave its possessor
extraordinary power...

183
00:21:26,827 --> 00:21:29,161
the power to control time.

184
00:21:29,204 --> 00:21:32,999
He called it the Triangle of Light.
Have you heard of it?

185
00:21:33,041 --> 00:21:35,126
No. No, I haven't.

186
00:21:40,215 --> 00:21:44,677
He always steered his own course,
your father.

187
00:21:45,345 --> 00:21:47,722
He was a great man.

188
00:21:50,392 --> 00:21:52,852
Would you like some port?

189
00:21:53,395 --> 00:21:56,230
-It's really very fine.
-No.

190
00:21:56,273 --> 00:21:58,774
I can't help you, Lara.

191
00:21:58,859 --> 00:22:03,154
This clock truly is mystery.

192
00:22:19,338 --> 00:22:20,796
[Phone ringing]

193
00:22:23,592 --> 00:22:25,468
-Hello.
-Lara?

194
00:22:25,552 --> 00:22:27,470
Hello, it's Mr. Wilson.

195
00:22:27,596 --> 00:22:31,474
Yes. Well, I....
You see, I had a second thought...

196
00:22:31,558 --> 00:22:33,726
about that clock.

197
00:22:34,478 --> 00:22:36,771
There is a man
who may be able to help you.

198
00:22:36,855 --> 00:22:40,524
l gave him your number.
His name is Manfred Powell.

199
00:22:40,609 --> 00:22:42,485
You should see him.

200
00:22:42,569 --> 00:22:44,904
Thank you. I will.

201
00:22:44,946 --> 00:22:47,615
-Goodbye, Lara.
-You take care.

202
00:22:47,699 --> 00:22:48,699
Thank you.

203
00:22:48,784 --> 00:22:49,784
[Splattering]

204
00:22:51,661 --> 00:22:52,912
Bugger.

205
00:23:11,431 --> 00:23:13,391
Forgive me.

206
00:23:27,322 --> 00:23:28,739
Lady Croft.

207
00:23:28,824 --> 00:23:31,575
-Ah, Mr. Powell.
-Oh, no, no, no. Good heavens, no.

208
00:23:31,660 --> 00:23:35,496
I'm actually his associate, Mr. Pimms.

209
00:23:35,789 --> 00:23:39,375
-Mr. Pimms?
-Yeah, like the beverage.

210
00:23:46,383 --> 00:23:49,343
[Soft instrumental music playing]

211
00:23:49,386 --> 00:23:51,053
Yeah, she's here.

212
00:23:54,683 --> 00:23:56,684
What does Mr. Powell do?

213
00:23:57,519 --> 00:24:00,229
He's a lawyer. I'm his law clerk.

214
00:24:00,313 --> 00:24:04,525
It's a fairly recent appointment,
but enjoying it, all the varied work.

215
00:24:05,527 --> 00:24:08,529
-A lawyer.
-Isn't it obvious?

216
00:24:10,157 --> 00:24:12,158
Lady Croft, my pleasure.

217
00:24:12,534 --> 00:24:15,536
-Manfred Powell, Q.C.
-Good morning.

218
00:24:15,620 --> 00:24:19,540
I believe you are quite an authority
on things ancient and mythological.

219
00:24:20,000 --> 00:24:21,041
Well, I travel.

220
00:24:21,084 --> 00:24:24,044
No, no, Mr. Wilson said
you were quite the archaeologist.

221
00:24:24,129 --> 00:24:25,379
Please.

222
00:24:26,381 --> 00:24:29,216
Oh, he's very sweet.

223
00:24:29,301 --> 00:24:31,635
He knew your father, I believe.

224
00:24:33,847 --> 00:24:36,056
Yes, they were great friends.

225
00:24:36,349 --> 00:24:39,810
I had the honor of meeting him
myself once, in Venice.

226
00:24:40,770 --> 00:24:43,522
I was so sorry to hear about his death.

227
00:24:48,778 --> 00:24:51,030
This is the clock I spoke of.

228
00:24:55,035 --> 00:24:56,702
Very interesting.

229
00:24:59,789 --> 00:25:02,625
It's a shame
you only brought photographs.

230
00:25:04,127 --> 00:25:07,755
Nevertheless, it is fascinating.

231
00:25:07,923 --> 00:25:10,841
You said it started ticking the night
of the alignment.

232
00:25:10,926 --> 00:25:12,009
Yes.

233
00:25:16,556 --> 00:25:19,225
-You said you were a lawyer?
-Yes.

234
00:25:19,935 --> 00:25:22,436
And the study of clocks is a hobby?

235
00:25:23,522 --> 00:25:25,356
This is an obsession.

236
00:25:26,483 --> 00:25:30,236
Really my specialty.
My practice centers around antiquities.

237
00:25:30,654 --> 00:25:32,780
But the origin of this clock...

238
00:25:32,822 --> 00:25:34,657
completely eludes me.

239
00:25:37,994 --> 00:25:40,037
I think I've never seen anything quite
so beautiful...

240
00:25:40,121 --> 00:25:42,289
that I know so little about.

241
00:25:47,587 --> 00:25:49,838
This is a pleasurable torment.

242
00:25:51,591 --> 00:25:53,509
My ignorance amuses me.

243
00:25:56,012 --> 00:26:01,892
"My ignorance amuses me."

244
00:26:02,477 --> 00:26:05,729
Yes, well, I've always found
your ignorance quite amusing.

245
00:26:05,814 --> 00:26:08,190
Powell, however, is not ignorant.

246
00:26:10,485 --> 00:26:11,944
He's a liar.

247
00:26:20,662 --> 00:26:22,746
[Classical instrumental music]

248
00:26:26,042 --> 00:26:28,919
-Anything you need?
-No. Thank you, Hillary.

249
00:26:29,004 --> 00:26:32,006
-Don't you stay up too late.
-I won't.

250
00:27:05,206 --> 00:27:06,665
[Techno music playing]

251
00:27:06,708 --> 00:27:07,708
[Humming]

252
00:27:10,670 --> 00:27:12,463
[Chattering over radios]

253
00:27:12,547 --> 00:27:15,007
MAN: [Over radio] Forward team,
wait for my command.

254
00:27:20,055 --> 00:27:23,390
ln position awaiting your order.

255
00:27:46,623 --> 00:27:48,082
[Electronic beeping]

256
00:27:55,924 --> 00:27:57,257
[Alarm bleeping]

257
00:28:47,142 --> 00:28:48,434
Bastards!

258
00:28:49,728 --> 00:28:51,311
Bloody hell!

259
00:28:56,985 --> 00:28:58,694
MAN: [Over radio] On the left.
On the left.

260
00:29:20,675 --> 00:29:22,843
